

Each New Job will have some tags:
    - Company name
    - Location
    - Department ( Engineering, Sales, etc)
    - Role Name ( MTS1, MTS3, SDE 1, Staff Engineer, etc)
    - Role field ( Storage, AI, Big Data, etc) ( future scope)
    - Programming language , tech stack ,etc  ( future scope)
    - Compensation Range ( future scope)
    - Years of experiences ( future scope - optional)


Each user will have some preferences and want to receive Job notifications as per his/her preferences only
Possible Preferences example:
    - (Company:Flipkart, Location-Bangalore, Role Name - SDE1), (Company:Amazon, Location-All locations, Role Name - SDE2), some more preferences
    - (Company - All companies, Location: Bangalore, Hyderabad, Role: SDE1, SDE2)

So a user can select any combination.




 => Flow
 Job -> Generate tags for job -> find all the user to whom this job notification needs to be sent -> sent notification to selected users


 => How to store into so that 'finding interested user' is scalable.
 Estimates( all guess are maximal)
 Total companies - 1000 ( guess- considering companies with good names and good pay)
 Total Location - 1000 ( guess -> on average 5-6 locations per country * 200 countries)
 Total departments - 15-20 only
 Total Role names -> 1000 ( random guess - as most roles names are same across companies)
 Remaining parameters are also limited

 User-> initially it will be around 40-50 ( upper limit 100) only
 If we make it available for all-> around 10,000 to 50,000


  -> Storage strategy 1
    For each user, store all the preferences he/she has

    User preference table
    user_id- int
    user_preferences- List of preferences( as described earlier)


    Pros -> simple- just check for each user, if the job tags are satisfied or not
    Cons -> too slow- need to check for each user and for each user, need to check entire list in worst case( can sort the list for by company name, etc- but still can be complete list scan in worst case)



    -> Storage strategy 2
    each company has around 20-30( worst case) locations and 50-60 role names -> so total of 1000*30*60 = 1800000 possible combination.
    These combinations, we can find from the data- whenever there is a job and its combination is not there, just update there.

    Preference table
    combination -> list of users interested in this combination

    When a user select all combination, we will add it into all possible companies and other combinations as per his preference

    Much faster -> single row read will give all the users.





=> For minimal viable product -> we can go with approach 1


    More works needs -> db size needed ( based on calculations).
    More pros and cons based on reads and writes and storage costs,






=> If we restrict user choices - then it can be made simple
User must select some roles ( SDE1, SDE2, etc or any other combination or all or None)
User must select some locations ( all location or any combination or None)
user must select companies.

When a new job comes, first check role, then list of locations , and then companies


once user have base preferences ( roles and locations)
for each role-location combination -> user can select list of companies






new solution -> for each user * possible roles * possible location -> store bitset like structure for all the companies.






In future - will create some group of companies ( based on pay range or some other parameters), so that user can subscribe to all of them at once, instead of subscribing one at a time







Final Approach

job_name * locations * company_names -> List of users interested in this combination